[vouwblad] Sermon of St. John the Baptist. The figure placed obliquely by and leaning on a tree trunk (on the right) appears as woman and seen from the front- in Paolo Veronese's Sermon of St. John in the Borghese, see Mostra di [Paolo] Veronese, Venice 1939, NÂ° 45 (the detail is reproduced on p. 47 [sic= p. 113]). Here also St. John points at Christ and there are oriental -turbaned- listeners: the turbaned figure on the left in Bruegel's painting reminiscent of [Gentile] Bellini - [Vittorio] Carpaccio. Could there not be a common prototype for Bruegel & Veronese? Bruegel's crowd might have a predecessor in the Bellini-Carpaccio circle. [Rodolfo] Palluchini in the catal[ogue] of the Mostra di Veronese gives detailed biography for the picture and dates it 'forse di poco antecente al ciclo d'affreschi di Maser' (which he dates in first half seventh decennium of XVI century). Shape of turban in Bruegel's picture on [onleesbaar] with thin point in centre cf. with turban of Negro King in Veronese's Adoration in Vienna ([onleesbaar], Veronese, Abb. 69, adest). Has the turkish turban been transmitted to Bruegel via Venice or was this turban general?
